'''''The Birch''''' is a national biannual undergraduate journal of [[Eastern European]] and [[Eurasia]]n culture. 

==History and profile==
''The Birch'' was established in 2004.<ref name="sla">{{cite news|title=The Birch|url=http://slavic.columbia.edu/department-journals/birch|accessdate=8 August 2016|work=Columbia University}}</ref> The journal, which is run by undergraduates at [[Columbia University]],<ref>{{cite news|title=Publications|url=http://www.columbia.edu/publications/student_periodicals.html|accessdate=8 August 2016|work=Columbia University}}</ref> is the first exclusively undergraduate journal of [[Slavic studies|Slavic]], Eastern European and Eurasian studies in America.<ref name="sla"/> It is published biannually, in fall and spring semesters.<ref name="sla"/> Any enrolled [[undergraduate]] can submit work to one of three sections: [[creative writing]], [[literary criticism]] and culture and affairs.<ref name="sla"/> ''The Birch'' has featured [[interviews]] with the children of [[Vladimir Mayakovsky]], [[Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn]] and [[Boris Pasternak]]. The Fall 2006 issue featured an interview with [[Eduard Shevardnadze]].

