{{Expand Russian|Мюллер, Владимир Карлович|date=February 2018}} '''Vladimir Karlovich Myuller'''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.amazon.co.uk/English-Russian-dictionary-Newspaper-anglo-russkiy-2007-08-02/dp/B01K2DDLQY/ref=sr_1_1/257-6845980-1782923?s=books&ie=UTF8&qid=1518034711&sr=1-1&refinements=p_27:Vladimir+Myuller|title=Big English-Russian dictionary Mueller 450000|last=Karlovich|first=Myuller Vladimir|date=1794|publisher=Slavyanskiy Dom Knigi}}</ref> ({{lang-ru|Владимир Карлович Мюллер}}; 24 May 1880 – unknown, {{c.}} December 1941), also '''Müller''', was a Russian [[linguist]] and [[lexicographer]]. Müller held a professorial degree and compiled the most popular English–Russian dictionary, which saw numerous reeditions<ref name ="Muller">{{cite web|url=http://www.mirpeterburga.ru/docs/online/fontanka_5_2010.pdf|script-title=ru:Профессор В. К. Мюллер|publisher =Mir Peterburga|author=Девель Людмила Александровна|accessdate=Aug 25, 2011|language=ru}}</ref> (some containing about 70,000 words and expressions<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lib.muohio.edu/multifacet/record/mu3ugb1423181|title=Anglo-russkiĭ slovarʹ / 70,000 slov i vyrazheniĭ. Sostavil V.K. Müller|publisher =Miami University Libraries|accessdate=Aug 25, 2011}}</ref>). Müller was also an expert on medieval [[dramaturgy]], particularly on [[William Shakespeare]]. He published ''The Drama and Theatre of Shakespear's Epoch'' (1925) and lectured Shakespeariana to [[Dmitry Likhachov]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gumer.info/bibliotek_Buks/Literat/lihach/3_01.php|script-title=ru:О себе|publisher =Gumer.info|author=Лихачев Д.|accessdate=Aug 25, 2011|language=ru}}</ref>
==Life== Müller was born in [[Moscow]], his father was a [[Baltic Germans|Baltic German]] from [[Riga]].<ref name="Yermolovich">{{cite book | author=Д. И. Ермолович| title =Открывая Мюллера| language =Russian}}</ref> Upon graduation from [[Moscow State University]], Müller continued studies in Oxford and London. In 1918, Müller became a Professor and lectured at various institutions.<ref name="Yermolovich"/> He was described as "sincere opponent of German [[militarism]]" by his student and noted scholar [[Igor Diakonov]].<ref name ="Diakonov">{{cite web|url=http://www.srcc.msu.su/uni-persona/site/authors/djakonov/9.htm|script-title=ru:Книга воспоминаний|publisher =Srcc.msu.su|author=И. М. Дьяконов|accessdate=Aug 25, 2011|language=ru}}</ref> Around 1915 Müller married Aleksandra Petrovna Gneusheva. In the 1920s Müller wrote multiple articles on English literature for ''[[Granat Encyclopedic Dictionary]]'', ''[[Great Soviet Encyclopedia]]'' and ''[[Literature Encyclopedia]]''.<ref name="Yermolovich"/> According to Diakonov, Müller saw the cause of transition from [[Old English]] to [[Middle English]] and the loss of external grammatical flexion in the plague epidemic of the 14th century.<ref name ="Diakonov"/> In 1926 Müller moved with his wife to [[Saint Petersburg]]. In the following year he began working on English dictionaries, together with [[Semyon Boyanus]].
The exact date of Müller's death is unknown. It is believed that both Vladimir Müller and his wife died during the [[siege of Leningrad]] in 1941.<ref name="Yermolovich"/> Müller's wife was an art scholar and worked in the [[National Library of Russia]].<ref name ="Muller"/>
